Part I¶

Using the following dataset: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mwaskom/seaborn-data/master/penguins.csv choose the most convenient graph to show the following, each question in one graph, using the library of your choice: (18 Marks)

1. The relationship between the penguin's bill length and bill depth for each species. (5 marks)

In [ ]:
## TODO: Check your attributes, make a graph using Matplotlib or Seaborn to show the relationship needed

#Importing python libraries
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

#Load the dataset
penguins_data = pd.read_csv('C:/Users/HP/Downloads/CSCN8000/LAB4_CSCN8000/data/penguins.csv')
penguins = pd.DataFrame(penguins_data)

# Create a scatter plot using seaborn
sns.scatterplot(data=penguins, x='bill_length_mm', y='bill_depth_mm', hue='species', palette='dark')

#Set plot labels and titles
plt.xlabel('Bill Length (mm)')
plt.ylabel('Bill Depth (mm)')
plt.title('Relationship between Penguin\'s Bill Length and Bill Depth for Each Species')

#Show thw plot
plt.show()

What do you observe from the graph? (2 marks)

Your answer here:

It is observed from the graph that:

  1. The lengths and depths of adelaide penguins' bills often vary greatly.
  2. Bill length and depth appear to be fairly constant in chinstrap penguins.
  3. The bill lengths of Gentoo penguins vary greatly, although the bill depths vary less.

Why did you choose this type of graph? (2 marks)

Your answer here:

Because a scatter plot may graphically represent correlations, make species comparison easier, identify outliers, and show data distribution, it is a good option for investigating and showing the link between the bill length and bill depth of each species of penguin.

2. Suitable graph of the mean BMI (BMI not body_mass weight_in_kg/height(m2)) of female and male penguins. (Assume the height is the flipper length) (5 marks)

In [ ]:
#Your answer here

# Calculate BMI (Body Mass Index)
penguins['bmi'] = penguins['body_mass_g'] / ((penguins['flipper_length_mm'] / 1000) ** 2)

# Create a bar plot using seaborn
sns.barplot(x='sex', y='bmi', data=penguins)

#Set plot labels and titles
plt.xlabel('Gender')
plt.ylabel('Mean BMI')
plt.title('Mean BMI of Female and Male Penguins')

#Show the plot
plt.show()

Convince the museum board

The Firehouse Museum claims they ran an event in 2014 that brought an incredible number of visitors, and that they should get extra budget to run a similar event again. The other museums think these types of events aren't that important, and budgets should be split purely based on recent visitors on an average day.

To show the museum board how the event compared to regular traffic at each museum, create a suitable chart that shows how the number of visitors to each museum evolved over time. (4 marks)

In [ ]:
#Your solution here
# Convert the 'Date' column to datetime format
museum_data['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(museum_data['Date'])

# Create a line chart to show the evolution of visitors over time for each museum
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

# Iterate through each museum and plot the number of visitors over time
for museum in museum_data.columns[1:]:
    plt.plot(museum_data['Date'], museum_data[museum], label=museum)

# Highlight the year 2014 for emphasis on the event
plt.axvline(pd.to_datetime('2014-01-01'), color='red', linestyle='--', label='Event Year (2014)')

# Set plot title and labels
plt.title('Evolution of Museum Visitors Over Time')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Number of Visitors')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)

# Show the plot
plt.show()

What did you observe from the graph? (2 marks)

Your answer here

From the graph it is observed that:

  1. Event Impact (2014): In 2014, there was a noticeable increase in the number of visitors to one or more museums.
  2. Comparative Trends: The graphic makes it possible to see how visiting patterns vary throughout museums.
  3. Long-term Patterns: Using the chart, one may determine any long-term trends or variations in museum attendance over time, which is helpful for planning a budget.

Why did you choose this type of graph? (2 marks)

You answer here

The line chart was used because it works well for displaying time-series data, making it easier to compare different museums, and clearly communicating information about how visitor numbers have changed over time, particularly the year of interest.

Is there anything interesting observed from the plot/graph? (1 mark)

Your answer here

The x-axis in this line graphic indicates the years, and each nation is represented by a line. The lines give each country's petrol price fluctuations over time a visual representation that makes trend detection and comparison simple.

  1. Trends Over Time: This graphic will demonstrate how each nation's petrol costs have changed over time.
  2. Comparisons by Country: It is simple to identify nations that exhibit comparable patterns or persistently higher or lower pricing.
  3. Outliers: Sudden increases or decreases in the price of petrol for a certain nation may be considered anomalies.
  4. Cross-Country Comparisons: By comparing the lines graphically, you can see which nations have, on average, higher or lower petrol costs over the course of the year.

Why did you choose this type of graph? (2 marks)

You answer here

Because a line plot effectively visualises temporal patterns and makes direct comparisons possible, I decided to use it to illustrate the link between petrol prices for each nation over the course of all years. When showing how a variable, like petrol prices, varies over a continuous period of time, line plots are a good choice since they make it possible to see patterns, fluctuations, and long-term trends. A clear and distinct visual depiction of how petrol prices have changed over the given time period is provided by the plot, where each line represents a nation.
